-- Regression: REG-02 crash-canary for IRON_HIR_EXPR_CLOSURE (lambda).
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 37-02's collect_mono_enums_node
-- walker crashed on if/elif/else lowering because of a locally-
-- shadowed struct typedef. Lambda expressions in Iron lower through
-- Iron_FuncDecl { is_lambda=true, captured_names[], body } and the
-- HIR walker must recurse into the body block to collect inner enum
-- construction sites (the Phase 37-02 pass). Walker cases that
-- handle CLOSURE but mis-recurse into the body silently drop every
-- statement inside the lambda -- the same class of "passes compile,
-- wrong at runtime" bug the Phase 37-02 motivating incident caused.
-- Phase 66 added -Werror=switch-enum and PROT-04 blind-cast fixes;
-- this canary is the runtime regression net.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** Iron_FuncDecl (is_lambda=true) carries
--   { span, kind, is_lambda, params[], return_type, body,
--     captured_names[], captured_count }
-- Walker cases that fail to recurse into `body` drop every statement
-- inside the lambda; cases that fail to collect captured_names drop
-- the closure environment.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Phase 67-08 added this fixture as a REG-02 crash
-- canary. Uses `func(x: Int) -> Int { ... }` lambda syntax (the
-- supported Iron form) stored in a val and called indirectly. No
-- captured outer state -- that is the companion fixture
-- hir_canary_closure_capture.iron. CI integration: runs in both
-- Debug and Release via Phase 66-04's build-and-test-release job.
--
-- **Severity.** H (regression potential) -- lambdas are exercised by
-- every functional-style Iron program, so a walker regression
-- produces silently wrong output on real code.

func main() {
  val double = func(x: Int) -> Int {
    return x * 2
  }
  val square = func(x: Int) -> Int {
    return x * x
  }
  val inc = func(x: Int) -> Int {
    return x + 1
  }
  val a = double(5)          -- 10
  val b = square(7)          -- 49
  val c = inc(square(3))     -- 10
  println("a: {a}")
  println("b: {b}")
  println("c: {c}")
  println("sum: {a + b + c}")
}
